Sections "PROJECT" contain missmatched items: {'PROJECT_SUMMARY': ["Against the backdrop of tightening arable land resources and intensified cultivation practices, continuous cropping obstacles and drought stress have emerged as critical abiotic constraints limiting sustainable agricultural development in China. Cassava, a crop with high photosynthetic potential, exhibits a significant yield gap in its primary production region of Guangxi, where actual tuberous root yields fall far below theoretical maxima due to the superimposed effects of prolonged continuous cropping and seasonal drought. Previous studies have demonstrated that the accumulation of phenolic acids in root exudates and the deterioration of soil physicochemical properties induced by continuous cassava cropping are exacerbated by drought-driven soil acidification, compaction, and the degradation of microbial community structure. These combined factors severely inhibit cassava growth and development, thereby contributing to China's heavy reliance on imported cassava products. To validate and extend these findings, we further performed untargeted metabolomic profiling of cassava roots subjected to the interactive stress of continuous cropping and drought, aiming to elucidate the underlying metabolic adaptation mechanisms. The results revealed that the combined stress profoundly remodeled both primary and secondary metabolic profiles in cassava roots, with the most pronounced alterations observed in the levels of phenolic acids, flavonoids, and amino acid derivatives. Notably, osmoregulatory compounds such as proline and betaine, as well as antioxidant-associated metabolites including ascorbic acid and glutathione, exhibited a synergistic accumulation pattern with increasing continuous cropping cycles and intensifying drought severity. Pathway enrichment analysis further indicated that phenylpropanoid biosynthesis, the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle, and glutathione metabolism were preferentially mobilized under the interactive stress conditions. Collectively, these metabolic lines of evidence provide a preliminary elucidation of the adaptive strategies employed by cassava to cope with the compound stress of continuous cropping and drought. The differential metabolites and key pathways identified herein offer a valuable theoretical foundation for future molecular breeding efforts aimed at enhancing tolerance to continuous cropping and drought, as well as for the development of improved high-yield cultivation practices", "Against the backdrop of tightening arable land resources and intensified cultivation practices, continuous cropping obstacles and drought stress have emerged as critical abiotic constraints limiting sustainable agricultural development in China. Cassava, a crop with high photosynthetic potential, exhibits a significant yield gap in its primary production region of Guangxi, where actual tuberous root yields fall far below theoretical maxima due to the superimposed effects of prolonged continuous cropping and seasonal drought. Previous studies have demonstrated that the accumulation of phenolic acids in root exudates and the deterioration of soil physicochemical properties induced by continuous cassava cropping are exacerbated by drought-driven soil acidification, compaction, and the degradation of microbial community structure. These combined factors severely inhibit cassava growth and development, thereby contributing to China''s heavy reliance on imported cassava products. To validate and extend these findings, we further performed untargeted metabolomic profiling of cassava roots subjected to the interactive stress of continuous cropping and drought, aiming to elucidate the underlying metabolic adaptation mechanisms. The results revealed that the combined stress profoundly remodeled both primary and secondary metabolic profiles in cassava roots, with the most pronounced alterations observed in the levels of phenolic acids, flavonoids, and amino acid derivatives. Notably, osmoregulatory compounds such as proline and betaine, as well as antioxidant-associated metabolites including ascorbic acid and glutathione, exhibited a synergistic accumulation pattern with increasing continuous cropping cycles and intensifying drought severity. Pathway enrichment analysis further indicated that phenylpropanoid biosynthesis, the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle, and glutathione metabolism were preferentially mobilized under the interactive stress conditions. Collectively, these metabolic lines of evidence provide a preliminary elucidation of the adaptive strategies employed by cassava to cope with the compound stress of continuous cropping and drought. The differential metabolites and key pathways identified herein offer a valuable theoretical foundation for future molecular breeding efforts aimed at enhancing tolerance to continuous cropping and drought, as well as for the development of improved high-yield cultivation practices"]}